He's in trouble.

26
00:01:27,694 --> 00:01:30,029
It's okay. We're all here to help.

27
00:01:30,196 --> 00:01:33,366
Yes, and this baby will have plenty
of manly role models.

28
00:01:33,533 --> 00:01:37,036
Now, I'm certain that whatever Bernadette
can't teach him, Penny can.

29
00:01:39,414 --> 00:01:41,749
- Oh, she can pee into a bottle.
PENNY: Mm-hm.

30
00:01:41,916 --> 00:01:44,669
Anything with a neck wider than a nickel.

31
00:01:46,087 --> 00:01:48,798
Howie, there's a lot of amazing things
you can teach a son.

32
00:01:48,965 --> 00:01:52,552
Yeah, you do always know
how to pick just the right antacid.

33
00:01:53,970 --> 00:01:58,057
I don't know if I can teach that.
It's just something I was born with.

34
00:01:58,224 --> 00:02:01,561
Come on. You can build things.
You were an astronaut.

35
00:02:01,728 --> 00:02:02,937
That's true.

36
00:02:03,104 --> 00:02:07,317
You know, as a kid, I used to make model
rockets. That'd be pretty cool to do with a son.

37
00:02:07,484 --> 00:02:09,944
Model rockets. Finally.
Something interesting.

38
00:02:10,737 --> 00:02:13,114
What is your preferred mode of recovery?

39
00:02:13,281 --> 00:02:15,450
Sheldon, we're helping our friends.

40
00:02:16,034 --> 00:02:18,495
And we got to model rockets.

41
00:02:18,661 --> 00:02:21,915
It was a tedious road,
but well worth the effort.

42
00:02:22,665 --> 00:02:25,502
- Have you thought of names?
- We finally got to model rockets.

43
00:02:25,668 --> 00:02:26,920
Why are you turning back?

44
00:02:53,279 --> 00:02:55,657
- Where you going?
- Back to the dry cleaner. Look.

45
00:02:55,823 --> 00:02:58,326
They didn't get the stain
out of my Starfleet uniform.

46
00:02:58,493 --> 00:03:01,454
Well, if you didn't make me
wear the green body paint in bed...

47
00:03:01,621 --> 00:03:03,998
you wouldn't have to
get it dry cleaned so much.

48
00:03:05,208 --> 00:03:06,751
No, it's worth it.

49
00:03:07,669 --> 00:03:08,920
[LAPTOP CHIMING]

50
00:03:09,087 --> 00:03:10,296
Hey, wait, it's your mom.

51
00:03:10,463 --> 00:03:12,632
Oh, too bad. She just missed me.

52
00:03:16,844 --> 00:03:17,887
Hey, Beverly.

53
00:03:18,054 --> 00:03:19,389
Oh, hello, Penny.

54
00:03:19,555 --> 00:03:22,934
Leonard just left. He's gonna be
so upset he missed your call.

55
00:03:23,101 --> 00:03:24,644
Why?

56
00:03:25,645 --> 00:03:27,021
Because he—

57
00:03:27,188 --> 00:03:29,399
Yeah, I don't know. How are you?

58
00:03:30,108 --> 00:03:32,277
Did you mean personally or professionally?

59
00:03:33,069 --> 00:03:35,905
Personally? Like, what'd you do last night?

60
00:03:36,072 --> 00:03:41,578
I had Cuban food at the home of a man
with whom I shared unsatisfying intercourse.

61
00:03:44,038 --> 00:03:46,791
Wow. Okay.

62
00:03:48,543 --> 00:03:50,712
And to anticipate your next questions...

63
00:03:50,878 --> 00:03:53,881
roasted pork and sideways missionary.

64
00:03:56,718 --> 00:03:59,887
Sure. Sure. Because you were full.

65
00:04:02,432 --> 00:04:05,143
I haven't looked at all this stuff in years.

66
00:04:05,310 --> 00:04:07,770
Had it. Had it.

67
00:04:07,937 --> 00:04:10,356
Burnt down my garage with it.

68
00:04:10,898 --> 00:04:12,775
I had three model rockets as a kid.

69
00:04:12,942 --> 00:04:15,695
And that was the largest
space program in India.

70
00:04:16,571 --> 00:04:18,656
You have a replica Saturn V?

71
00:04:18,823 --> 00:04:22,285
Yeah, my dad bought it
before he, you know...

72
00:04:22,452 --> 00:04:24,245
abandoned our family.

73
00:04:24,412 --> 00:04:26,372
Lucky duck.

74
00:04:27,999 --> 00:04:31,169
I could never bring myself
to open it without him.

75
00:04:31,336 --> 00:04:32,670
It's silly.

76
00:04:32,837 --> 00:04:33,880
That's not silly.

77
00:04:34,047 --> 00:04:37,508
I always wanted my dad to build
rockets with me, but he wasn't interested.

78
00:04:37,675 --> 00:04:39,677
Yes. Disappointing fathers.

79
00:04:39,844 --> 00:04:41,220
Tell me about it.

80
00:04:41,387 --> 00:04:44,307
I remember for my 16th birthday,
my dad bought me a Mercedes.

81
00:04:44,474 --> 00:04:47,268
Like, a little one. Like, a starter Mercedes.

82
00:04:48,519 --> 00:04:51,648
He had barely handed me the keys
before he had to rush back to work.

83
00:04:51,814 --> 00:04:55,610
I didn't see him again till,
like, pretty late that night.

84
00:04:58,321 --> 00:04:59,572
Anyway...

85
00:05:01,824 --> 00:05:05,036
as angry as I was with him leaving...

86
00:05:05,203 --> 00:05:08,498
building this stuff is probably
what led me to become an engineer.

87
00:05:08,665 --> 00:05:13,169
I suppose, in his own way,
my dad also encouraged me to pursue science.

88
00:05:13,336 --> 00:05:16,714
I mean, he is the one that taught me
that flatulence is combustible.

89
00:05:18,257 --> 00:05:21,761
And also,
polyester gym shorts don't burn.

90
00:05:22,261 --> 00:05:23,888
They melt.

91
00:05:24,764 --> 00:05:29,644
Yeah, I guess I'm an astrophysicist because
as a kid I said I liked to look at the stars.

92
00:05:29,811 --> 00:05:32,647
So my dad sent me to Hawaii
to visit the Keck telescope.

93
00:05:36,025 --> 00:05:37,610
Screw you. My pain is real.

94
00:05:42,031 --> 00:05:44,117
You know what, forget the past.

95
00:05:44,617 --> 00:05:47,328
What do you say
you and me build this rocket.

96
00:05:47,870 --> 00:05:50,873
That sounds like it could be
a real bonding experience for us.

97
00:05:51,040 --> 00:05:52,667
- Right?
- Oh, I see.

98
00:05:52,834 --> 00:05:54,877
You think that's a positive.

99
00:05:59,424 --> 00:06:02,051
So you didn't wanna hang out
with Sheldon and Howard?

100
00:06:02,218 --> 00:06:04,720
No, they were bonding
over their sad childhoods.

101
00:06:04,887 --> 00:06:08,182
And my stupid parents
were always there for me.

102
00:06:09,809 --> 00:06:10,852
What's all this?

103
00:06:11,018 --> 00:06:15,148
I'm just boxing up all the clothes Halley's
outgrown. Guess we won't need them anymore.

104
00:06:15,314 --> 00:06:18,568
Slow down. I'm sure there's some
you could reuse for a boy.

105
00:06:19,235 --> 00:06:21,112
"Daddy's little girl"?

106
00:06:21,904 --> 00:06:24,407
Okay, well, what if we change it to say:

107
00:06:24,574 --> 00:06:26,701
"Daddy's little girl magnet."

108
00:06:26,868 --> 00:06:28,411
Boom, boy shirt.

109
00:06:30,496 --> 00:06:31,664
What about this?

110
00:06:31,831 --> 00:06:33,082
Okay.

111
00:06:33,249 --> 00:06:37,211
Pull off the skirt, slap a lightning bolt
on the front, and you've got Baby Flash.

112
00:06:38,087 --> 00:06:41,841
Oh! Stick a long sleeve under it.
Boom, Baby Sheldon.

113
00:06:43,968 --> 00:06:46,345
- Wow, you're really good at this.
- Oh, please.

114
00:06:46,512 --> 00:06:50,016
This isn't my first time
turning girl clothes into boy clothes.

115
00:06:51,225 --> 00:06:53,186
Why?
You got your sister's hand-me-downs?

116
00:06:54,103 --> 00:06:56,147
Yeah, that.

117
00:07:00,109 --> 00:07:02,612
Oh, I should've brought peanuts.

118
00:07:02,778 --> 00:07:04,822
You can't eat peanuts. You're allergic.

119
00:07:05,281 --> 00:07:08,075
If you die, who's going to drive me home?

120
00:07:08,242 --> 00:07:10,953
I'm not gonna eat them.
It's a thing they do at JPL.

121
00:07:11,120 --> 00:07:14,499
When the Ranger mission had a successful
launch, there were peanuts in the room.

122
00:07:14,665 --> 00:07:17,293
Ever since then,
they have them at every launch.

123
00:07:17,794 --> 00:07:19,879
That sounds like a silly superstition.

124
00:07:20,713 --> 00:07:22,340
It's more of a tradition.

125
00:07:22,507 --> 00:07:24,801
Ohh! I do love a tradition.

126
00:07:26,302 --> 00:07:28,554
Pull over at the next peanut store.

127
00:07:29,806 --> 00:07:31,432
I don't think that's a real thing.

128
00:07:31,599 --> 00:07:34,477
Oh, don't be pedantic.
Any nut store will do.

129
00:07:35,728 --> 00:07:38,940
I don't think we can get peanuts out here.

130
00:07:39,106 --> 00:07:41,442
Oh, well, then this whole day's ruined.

131
00:07:42,902 --> 00:07:46,197
Now that I think about it,
maybe it is more of a superstition.

132
00:07:46,364 --> 00:07:48,741
Whew. That was close.

133
00:07:52,912 --> 00:07:55,164
[CELL PHONE CHIMING]

134
00:07:56,582 --> 00:07:59,585
Oh, hey, Beverly.
You called my phone, not Leonard's.

135
00:07:59,752 --> 00:08:02,463
Actually, I was hoping to speak with you.

136
00:08:02,630 --> 00:08:04,173
Is this a good time?

137
00:08:05,675 --> 00:08:07,718
That depends.
What time is it where you are?

138
00:08:07,885 --> 00:08:08,970
Just after 5.

139
00:08:09,971 --> 00:08:12,765
Ahem. Yeah, that counts. What's up?

140
00:08:14,559 --> 00:08:16,936
Well, I enjoyed
our conversation the other day.

141
00:08:17,103 --> 00:08:19,146
And I was hoping to continue it.

142
00:08:19,313 --> 00:08:20,439
Really?

143
00:08:20,606 --> 00:08:22,692
Yes. You may find this surprising...

144
00:08:22,859 --> 00:08:25,987
but I don't have a lot of
what you would call "girlfriends."

145
00:08:26,779 --> 00:08:28,865
What?

146
00:08:30,491 --> 00:08:32,994
Of course there are my female colleagues...

147
00:08:33,160 --> 00:08:35,162
but they're all Freudians.

148
00:08:35,329 --> 00:08:40,209
So the only boy that I can
dish about is my father. Ha-ha-ha.

149
00:08:45,381 --> 00:08:48,092
Well, I'm here for you.
What do you wanna talk about?

150
00:08:48,259 --> 00:08:51,137
Well, last time, we focused on my life.

151
00:08:51,304 --> 00:08:55,099
If we're going to be real girlfriends,
we should talk about you as well.

152
00:08:55,266 --> 00:08:57,268
Well, if we're gonna be real girlfriends...

153
00:08:57,435 --> 00:09:00,521
we should get a third girl
we can trash behind her back.

154
00:09:01,731 --> 00:09:03,941
Oh, so we'd be catty.

155
00:09:04,108 --> 00:09:05,943
Oh, I like it.

156
00:09:06,611 --> 00:09:08,446
What about Sheldon's fiancé?

157
00:09:08,613 --> 00:09:11,115
She seems a bit dour.

158
00:09:13,409 --> 00:09:16,412
"Dour"? Meow.

159
00:09:20,875 --> 00:09:22,668
All right. Here we go.

160
00:09:22,835 --> 00:09:24,462
L-minus-ten.

161
00:09:24,629 --> 00:09:26,088
- Nine.
- What are you doing?

162
00:09:26,255 --> 00:09:27,465
It's "T-minus."

163
00:09:27,632 --> 00:09:29,967
I was an astronaut. We used "L-minus."

164
00:09:30,384 --> 00:09:33,930
Yeah, but this is a Saturn V. When they
launched those, they said, "T-minus."

165
00:09:34,096 --> 00:09:36,349
It's my rocket. We're doing it my way.

166
00:09:37,934 --> 00:09:39,143
Fine.

167
00:09:40,978 --> 00:09:44,774
I'm not saying I know why your dad left,
but I think I'm getting an idea.

168
00:09:46,984 --> 00:09:51,280
L-minus-ten, night, eight, seven, six—

169
00:09:51,447 --> 00:09:53,282
Because you're kind of bossy.

170
00:09:54,867 --> 00:09:59,288
Five, four, three, two, one.

171
00:10:04,293 --> 00:10:06,796
I remember them going up higher.

172
00:10:10,216 --> 00:10:11,384
Well, that's perfect.

173
00:10:11,550 --> 00:10:16,055
The one thing I thought I could
do with my son. I can't even do that right.

174
00:10:16,222 --> 00:10:18,849
If you wanna see it again, I got it on video.

175
00:10:19,600 --> 00:10:21,852
It's pretty cool in slow motion.

176
00:10:22,520 --> 00:10:24,021
Thank you for your support.

177
00:10:24,188 --> 00:10:26,232
- You're welcome.
- I was being sarcastic.

178
00:10:26,399 --> 00:10:27,733
How dare you?

179
00:10:30,111 --> 00:10:32,279
Sheldon, what am I gonna do?

180
00:10:33,280 --> 00:10:36,325
What do I know about raising a boy?

181
00:10:37,410 --> 00:10:40,037
What do you know about raising a girl?

182
00:10:41,622 --> 00:10:42,873
Oh, my God.

183
00:10:43,040 --> 00:10:44,375
You're right.

184
00:10:45,292 --> 00:10:47,461
Well, I don't know
if that was sarcasm or not.

185
00:10:47,628 --> 00:10:50,840
So either, "You're welcome," or "Hey."

186
00:10:55,761 --> 00:10:57,096
[CELL PHONE CHIMES]

187
00:10:59,098 --> 00:11:03,978
Leonard, did you really just text me from the
couch to put extra mustard on your sandwich?

188
00:11:05,021 --> 00:11:07,606
I was worried
you might not check your e-mail.

189
00:11:09,775 --> 00:11:10,818
[CELL PHONE CHIMES]

190
00:11:10,985 --> 00:11:14,405
- I swear to God I will throw this out.
- That one was not me.

191
00:11:14,572 --> 00:11:16,198
Oh, wait. It's just your mom.

192
00:11:16,741 --> 00:11:17,950
My mother's texting you?

193
00:11:18,117 --> 00:11:19,994
Yeah, we've been talking a lot lately.

194
00:11:20,161 --> 00:11:21,954
Why?

195
00:11:22,580 --> 00:11:25,916
Is she sick of talking
to the Magic Mirror on the wall?

196
00:11:27,042 --> 00:11:30,004
No, I thinks she's lonely.
She's been reaching out.

197
00:11:30,921 --> 00:11:35,009
Okay, just be careful.
You think you're getting close to her.

198
00:11:35,176 --> 00:11:37,845
The next thing you know,
you're featured in a book called:

199
00:11:38,012 --> 00:11:41,432
He's Doing It on Purpose:
Raising a Teenage Bed Wetter.

200
00:11:42,641 --> 00:11:44,185
No, it's not like that.

201
00:11:44,351 --> 00:11:46,645
You know, she's been
opening up about her life.

202
00:11:46,812 --> 00:11:48,856
She's been really supportive about mine.

203
00:11:49,023 --> 00:11:50,274
- Really?
- Yeah.

204
00:11:50,441 --> 00:11:53,527
I've been telling her about my job.
She said she was proud of me.

205
00:11:54,653 --> 00:11:56,655
Well, that's great.

206
00:11:58,824 --> 00:12:00,785
She never told me she was proud of me.

207
00:12:02,828 --> 00:12:05,331
Even when I stayed dry for a whole month.

208
00:12:07,333 --> 00:12:09,293
Do you not want me
to be friends with your mom?

209
00:12:09,460 --> 00:12:11,003
Well, let's be clear.

210
00:12:11,170 --> 00:12:13,798
I married you to hurt her.

211
00:12:17,009 --> 00:12:18,761
You're kind of ruining it.

212
00:12:21,972 --> 00:12:24,683
Reason number 13 to feel good:

213
00:12:24,850 --> 00:12:26,769
As a launch, it was bad.

214
00:12:26,977 --> 00:12:29,688
But as an explosion, it was glorious.

215
00:12:31,357 --> 00:12:32,942
Reason 14:

216
00:12:33,108 --> 00:12:35,694
You still have all your fingers.

217
00:12:35,861 --> 00:12:38,739
And boys prefer a dad with fingers.

218
00:12:39,240 --> 00:12:42,535
Thanks for trying, but you're not
gonna be able to cheer me up.

219
00:12:42,993 --> 00:12:44,578
Well, how about this then?

220
00:12:44,745 --> 00:12:48,332
You quit your whining before I give you
something to cry about, young man.

221
00:12:49,542 --> 00:12:50,543
What?

222
00:12:51,001 --> 00:12:54,421
Those are comforting words
my father would often say.

223
00:12:55,214 --> 00:12:56,257
Did it help?

224
00:12:56,882 --> 00:12:59,677
I turned out great. You tell me.

225
00:13:01,345 --> 00:13:02,388
Let's get going.

226
00:13:03,013 --> 00:13:04,974
You gonna be this mopey
all the way home?

227
00:13:05,140 --> 00:13:06,809
I don't know. Maybe.

228
00:13:06,976 --> 00:13:10,479
There any chance you'd be cheered up
by an amazing trigonometry riddle?

229
00:13:12,815 --> 00:13:16,610
Well, if you can't answer that,
there's no way you're gonna get this riddle.

230
00:13:23,117 --> 00:13:25,828
Oh, hey. Hey, what do you think?

231
00:13:26,412 --> 00:13:30,708
Just because it's a boy, I don't think you need
to put a picture of genitals on his shirt.

232
00:13:31,250 --> 00:13:34,378
What? That's a baseball bat
with two little baseballs.

233
00:13:34,545 --> 00:13:37,006
Okay, yeah, now I see it.

234
00:13:39,091 --> 00:13:40,134
So, you know...

235
00:13:40,301 --> 00:13:45,264
I understand why Howard is nervous about
having a son, but are you really upset about it?

236
00:13:45,431 --> 00:13:48,809
No, I'm fine.
It's just, I grew up with a bunch of brothers.

237
00:13:48,976 --> 00:13:52,646
So I thought it'd be nice for Halley
to have a sister. Is that wrong?

238
00:13:52,813 --> 00:13:56,817
Of course it's wrong. You don't know
what this little boy's gonna be like.

239
00:13:56,984 --> 00:13:58,652
Maybe he'll be rough and tumble.

240
00:13:58,819 --> 00:14:00,988
Or maybe he'll be sweet and sensitive.

241
00:14:01,155 --> 00:14:03,782
Or maybe he'll be all those things, like me.

242
00:14:06,702 --> 00:14:08,329
You're rough and tumble?

243
00:14:10,039 --> 00:14:12,291
You bet I am, bitch.

244
00:14:14,919 --> 00:14:18,631
But I'm also sensitive
and regret saying that.

245
00:14:21,842 --> 00:14:23,219
[KNOCK ON DOOR]

246
00:14:23,928 --> 00:14:25,304
- Hey.
- Hello.

247
00:14:26,096 --> 00:14:27,723
You got a sec?

248
00:14:27,890 --> 00:14:29,516
Sure, what's up?

249
00:14:29,892 --> 00:14:32,061
Penny's been talking to my mother
like they're best friends.

250
00:14:32,228 --> 00:14:34,188
And it's kind of freaking me out.

251
00:14:34,813 --> 00:14:36,273
Okay.

252
00:14:36,899 --> 00:14:40,110
I am pretty sure they're not best friends.

253
00:14:43,656 --> 00:14:46,909
Because you can only have one best friend.

254
00:14:48,077 --> 00:14:51,247
And Penny has that, and, tsk, it's me.

255
00:14:53,249 --> 00:14:55,542
Oh, really? Is she FaceTiming
with you right now?

256
00:14:55,709 --> 00:14:57,044
She's FaceTiming with my mom.

257
00:14:57,211 --> 00:15:00,089
And believe me,
that is not a face you want to spend time with.

258
00:15:01,799 --> 00:15:06,720
Hm. Well, I have been pretty busy lately.
Maybe I've been neglecting our friendship.

259
00:15:06,929 --> 00:15:10,599
Penny knows I have a complicated relationship
with my mother. She doesn't care.

260
00:15:10,766 --> 00:15:15,646
And with everything going on at the lab and
planning the wedding, I have so little free time.

261
00:15:15,813 --> 00:15:18,399
Penny doesn't know
how manipulative my mother can be.

262
00:15:18,565 --> 00:15:22,278
Did you know there's such a thing as
reverse-reverse-reverse psychology?

263
00:15:22,945 --> 00:15:24,947
Because there is.

264
00:15:25,114 --> 00:15:28,409
She must feel so abandoned.
She's used to me being there all the time.

265
00:15:28,575 --> 00:15:31,787
But now I have my own life,
and she's just gonna have to accept it.

266
00:15:31,954 --> 00:15:34,581
And why is my mom
proud of Penny and not me?

267
00:15:34,748 --> 00:15:37,710
The question is: why is Penny
afraid of me growing as a person?

268
00:15:37,876 --> 00:15:41,171
- I'm good at stuff too.
- I deserve my own life.

269
00:15:44,133 --> 00:15:46,593
- Okay, well, thanks.
- Yeah, good talk.

270
00:15:52,891 --> 00:15:54,768
You know, studies have shown that...

271
00:15:54,935 --> 00:15:59,648
people distracted by emotional issues
are poor drivers.

272
00:15:59,815 --> 00:16:04,028
What about people distracted
by irritating passengers?

273
00:16:05,279 --> 00:16:09,992
That would be hard to test because
irritating is a subjective quality.

274
00:16:10,159 --> 00:16:12,661
Strongly disagree.

275
00:16:17,958 --> 00:16:19,043
Can I drive?

276
00:16:19,710 --> 00:16:21,795
No, you can't drive.

277
00:16:21,962 --> 00:16:23,797
You don't even have a license.

278
00:16:23,964 --> 00:16:25,049
Actually, I do.

279
00:16:25,591 --> 00:16:27,009
Really?

280
00:16:27,176 --> 00:16:28,218
Since when?

281
00:16:28,385 --> 00:16:29,428
Three years ago.

282
00:16:29,595 --> 00:16:32,348
I went on a bit of a license kick.

283
00:16:32,514 --> 00:16:35,142
I'm also a commercial fisherman.

284
00:16:36,226 --> 00:16:38,937
Then why don't you ever drive yourself?

285
00:16:39,104 --> 00:16:40,773
Honestly, I barely passed my test.

286
00:16:40,939 --> 00:16:43,734
And the one time I drove on my own,
I made a U-turn...

287
00:16:43,901 --> 00:16:47,071
got dizzy, threw up and walked home.

288
00:16:48,697 --> 00:16:50,366
You really wanna drive?

289
00:16:50,532 --> 00:16:52,326
It seems like the perfect time.

290
00:16:52,493 --> 00:16:55,245
The roads are straight.
There's no one around.

291
00:16:55,412 --> 00:16:58,165
And you don't seem to care
if you live or die.

292
00:16:59,625 --> 00:17:02,044
Live, Sheldon. I wanna live.

293
00:17:02,544 --> 00:17:05,214
That makes things a little trickier,
but I'll do my best.

294
00:17:07,883 --> 00:17:09,218
[DIAL TONE ON LAPTOP]

295
00:17:09,760 --> 00:17:13,013
Hi, Penn— Oh, hello, Leonard.

296
00:17:14,890 --> 00:17:16,266
Hello, Mother. How are you?

297
00:17:16,433 --> 00:17:18,394
- Fine, and you?
- I'm great.

298
00:17:18,560 --> 00:17:20,521
- Well, it's been lovely catching up.
- No.

299
00:17:20,687 --> 00:17:23,148
Wait, hang on. We need to talk.

300
00:17:23,315 --> 00:17:25,442
Oh, brother.

301
00:17:26,443 --> 00:17:29,655
I wanna know why aren't you proud of me.

302
00:17:30,614 --> 00:17:34,076
Well, isn't the real question
why aren't you proud of yourself?

303
00:17:34,243 --> 00:17:36,745
No, that is a question.

304
00:17:36,912 --> 00:17:39,456
And I ask it a lot.

305
00:17:39,623 --> 00:17:41,917
But let's stick with the one I asked you.

306
00:17:42,626 --> 00:17:44,628
Well, why do you think
I'm not proud of you?

307
00:17:44,795 --> 00:17:46,964
Because you never say it.

308
00:17:47,131 --> 00:17:51,135
But two days into chatting with Penny,
and you can't stop telling her how great she is.

309
00:17:51,301 --> 00:17:52,386
She is great.

310
00:17:52,553 --> 00:17:57,933
Honestly, of all of my children's spouses,
she's the one that I'm most impressed by.

311
00:17:59,435 --> 00:18:01,061
- Seriously?
- Yes.

312
00:18:01,228 --> 00:18:05,649
She's confident. She's thoughtful.
And she never complained about you once.

313
00:18:05,816 --> 00:18:08,735
I know what kind of strength that takes.

314
00:18:10,320 --> 00:18:12,406
So Penny's your favorite.

315
00:18:12,906 --> 00:18:14,700
I suppose she is.

316
00:18:14,867 --> 00:18:16,410
You married well, Leonard.

317
00:18:16,577 --> 00:18:19,121
And for that, I am proud of you.

318
00:18:22,124 --> 00:18:24,585
I don't know what to say.

319
00:18:24,751 --> 00:18:28,338
I'm also proud of how hard
you're trying not to cry.

320
00:18:30,466 --> 00:18:31,675
Thank you.

321
00:18:32,468 --> 00:18:35,179
- Would you like to hang up now?
- Yeah, here it comes.

322
00:18:42,936 --> 00:18:45,189
Your hands are at 10 and 2. Good.

323
00:18:45,355 --> 00:18:47,608
Steady on the gas.

324
00:18:47,774 --> 00:18:49,401
Okay.

325
00:18:49,568 --> 00:18:53,071
Now, you're gonna
wanna slowly switch lanes.

326
00:18:53,238 --> 00:18:55,741
- Why?
- Because there are only two...

327
00:18:55,908 --> 00:18:58,160
and you're not in either of them.

328
00:19:02,831 --> 00:19:04,625
Attaboy. Well done.

329
00:19:04,791 --> 00:19:05,834
Thank you.

330
00:19:06,001 --> 00:19:10,005
The last time I drove,
I was terrified, but this is fun.

331
00:19:10,172 --> 00:19:11,757
You're doing great.

332
00:19:11,924 --> 00:19:14,092
You're a good teacher.

333
00:19:16,595 --> 00:19:20,265
Your son is going to be lucky
to have you as a father.

334
00:19:21,683 --> 00:19:23,393
Thanks.

335
00:19:25,646 --> 00:19:29,066
Do you think I could try going a little faster?

336
00:19:29,483 --> 00:19:32,069
- Go for it, champ.
- Ow.

337
00:19:33,654 --> 00:19:36,448
Sorry. Just ease on the gas and—

338
00:19:36,615 --> 00:19:37,991
Too much. Too much.

339
00:19:38,158 --> 00:19:40,536
Why was I scared of this?
This is exhilarating.

340
00:19:40,702 --> 00:19:41,995
No, it's not. Slow down.

341
00:19:42,162 --> 00:19:44,373
Don't tell me what to do.
You're not my father.

342
00:19:52,839 --> 00:19:56,552
- You know how fast you were going?
- A hundred and twelve.

343
00:19:58,637 --> 00:19:59,888
Let me see your license.

344
00:20:02,015 --> 00:20:03,934
- Okay, here's the plan.
- No.

345
00:20:05,978 --> 00:20:07,521
Fine.

346
00:20:07,854 --> 00:20:09,606
There you go.

347
00:20:11,358 --> 00:20:13,902
You know what, you can just keep it.

